2 REGRESSION

The regression analysis is a useful tool to asses the correlation between two variables, named respectively x and y, where the first is the PREDICTOR and INDIPENDENT variable, while the second is the RESPONSE and DEPENDENT variable. We can perform a variety of regression analysis on the data, those includes, Simple Linear, Multiple Linear and Polynomial Regression

2.1 SIMPLE LINEAR REGRESSION

In the case of a simple linear regression the relation can be expressed by the formula “Y = b0 + b1X”, where b0 is the value of Y when X is 0, and b1 is the value of Y when X is 1. Let’s practice with some data. Look for the correlation between the Arrival Delay and Departure Delay for the Reporting Airline “Alaska”.

alaska_delay <- data_airline |>
  filter(CarrierDelay != "NA", Reporting_Airline == "AA")

head(alaska_delay)

linear_model <- lm(ArrDelayMinutes ~ DepDelayMinutes, data = alaska_delay)

Printing the summary, we can find out the values of b0 and b1, that in that case are 17.354 and 0.7523. We can now perform a prediction on three new value based on the training data set that we just executed.

new_depdelay <- data.frame(
  DepDelayMinutes = c(12, 19, 24)
)

predicted_value <- predict(linear_model, newdata = new_depdelay, interval = "confidence")

predicted_value
##        fit      lwr      upr

We receive a table with three columns values. The first, fit, is the most common value that we are probably going to incur into; the other two, lwr and the upr, are the lowest and highest value of a confident range of occurrence. To visualize the coefficients we may filter the data set with the $.

2.2 MULTIPLE LINEAR REGRESSION

The multiple linear regression can perform prediction on a variable, in that case the Arrival Delay, based on the analysis of different predictor variables. Taking into consideration the simple linear regression formula, we can add the new variable consideration at the end of it. It would now be “Y = b0 + b1X1 + b2X2”. Let’s practice with the predictor variables of DepDelayMinutes and LateAircraftDelay.

multiple_model <- lm(ArrDelayMinutes ~ DepDelayMinutes + LateAircraftDelay, data = alaska_delay)

summary(multiple_model)

2.3 ASSESSING MODELS VISUALLY

2.3.1 REGRESSING PLOT

Once we have different analysis, we have to asses which one of them has the best fit and to do so we can use the Regression plot to have a visual understanding of the relation. Using “ggplot()” we can achieve a set of charts. Let’s do the analysis on the Departure and Arrival delay regression.

alaska_delay |>
  ggplot(aes(DepDelayMinutes, ArrDelayMinutes)) +
  geom_point(col = "blue") +
  stat_smooth(method = "lm", col = "blue") +
  theme_minimal()
## `geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'

We can see from this plot that Arrival Delay Minutes is positively correlated to Departure Delay Minutes, since the regression slope is positive.

2.4 RESIDUAL PLOT

A residual plot analyzes the difference between the Observed Values and the Predicted Values and suggest the best fit for regression model by the chart result.

We have to first include in the data, a new column with the predicted values so we can compare the predicted with the observed. To do so we can use the linear model used at the beginning of the chapter.

alaska_model2 <- data_airline |>
  filter(Reporting_Airline == "AA", CarrierDelay != "NA")

linear_model_alaska <- lm(ArrDelayMinutes ~ DepDelayMinutes, data = alaska_model2)

alaska_model2$PredictedDelay <- predict(linear_model_alaska)

3 POLYNOMIAL REGRESSION

Polynomial regression is a particular case of the general linear regression model or multiple linear regression models. That is, although the data is nonlinear in polynomial regression (the predicator variables have higher order terms), the model in all cases is linear. (I dati sono sinuosi nel grafico ma la analisi che stiamo eseguendo è per trovare una linea lineare generale che lo possa descrivere, guarda il grafico per capire a pieno) Let’s make an example.

x <- seq(from = 0, to = 20, by = 0.1)

y <- 500 + 0.4 * (x-10)^3

noise <- rnorm(length(x), mean = 10, sd = 80)

noisy.y <- y + noise

The representation would look like that

ggplot(data = NULL, aes(x, noisy.y)) +
  geom_point(color = "blue", alpha = 0.3) +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm") +
  theme_minimal()
## `geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'

Instead, to have a very closer line representation, we can introduce in the “geom_smooth()” argument, the formula “formula = y ~ poly(x, 5)” where 5 is the exponential factor.

ggplot(data = NULL, aes(x, noisy.y)) +
  geom_point(color = "blue", alpha = 0.3) +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", formula = y ~ poly ( x, 5)) +
  theme_minimal()

We can also create a second level model.

time <- 6:19
temp <- c(4,6,7,9,10,11,11.5,12,12,11.5,11,10,9,8)

ggplot(data = NULL, aes(time, temp)) +
  geom_point(color = "blue", alpha = 0.3) +
  theme_minimal()

poly_model <- lm(temp ~ poly(time, 2, raw = TRUE))
ggplot(data = NULL, aes(time, temp)) + 
    geom_point(color = "blue", alpha = 0.3) +
    geom_smooth(method = "lm", formula = y ~ poly(x, 2)) +
  theme_minimal()

4 ASSESSING THE MODEL

In order to asses the best fit model, we have to refer to numeric values to see which is more accurate. Those information are related to the “R SQUARE” and the “MEAN SQUARED ERROR”. The first is a coefficient that shows how close are the results from the actual data in a percentage format; the second is an average of square errors that is the difference between the actual and estimated values, it has also a variant that is the “ROOT MEAN SQAURED ERROR”, that is the square root of the MEAN “SQUArED ERROR”.

Let’s now calculate the two values for each model we did previously.

*LINEAR MODEL**

summary(linear_model)$r.squared
## [1] 0.7588008
MeanSquaredError <- mean(linear_model$residuals^2)

MeanSquaredError
## [1] 394.0639
RSquaredError <- sqrt(MeanSquaredError)

RSquaredError
## [1] 19.85104

5 CONCLUSIONS

What is a good R-squared value? When comparing models, the model with the higher R-squared value is a better fit for the data.

What is a good MSE? When comparing models, the model with the smallest MSE value is a better fit for the data.
